By the early 1980\'92s, the Computer Science community at Carnegie Mellon was making heavy use of online bulletin boards or \'93bboards\'94.\'a0 These were a precursor of today\'92s newsgroups, and they were an important social mechanism in the department \'96 a place where faculty, staff, and students could discuss the weighty matters of the day on an equal footing.\'a0 Many of the posts were serious: talk announcements, requests for information, and things like \'93I\'92ve just found a ring in the fifth-floor men\'92s room.\'a0 Who does it belong to?\'94\'a0 Other posts discussed topics of general interest, ranging from politics to abortion to campus parking to keyboard layout (in increasing order of passion).\'a0 Even in those days, extended \'93flame wars\'94 were common.\
\'a0\
Given the nature of the community, a good many of the posts were humorous (or attempted humor).\'a0 The problem was that if someone made a sarcastic remark, a few readers would fail to get the joke, and each of them would post a lengthy diatribe in\'a0 response.\'a0 That would stir up more people with more responses, and soon the original thread of the discussion was buried.\'a0 In at least one case, a humorous remark was interpreted by someone as a serious safety warning.\
\'a0\
This problem caused some of us to suggest (only half seriously) that maybe it would be a good idea to explicitly mark posts that were not to be taken seriously.\'a0\'a0 After all, when using text-based online communication, we lack the body language or tone-of-voice cues that convey this information when we talk in person or on the phone.\'a0 Various \'93joke markers\'94\'a0 were suggested, and in the midst of that discussion it occurred to me that the character sequence :-) would be an elegant solution \'96 one that could be handled by the ASCII-based\'a0 computer terminals of the day.\'a0 So I suggested that.\'a0 In the same post, I also suggested the use of\'a0 :-(\'a0 to indicate that a message was meant to be taken seriously, though that symbol quickly evolved into a marker for displeasure, frustration, or anger.\
\'a0\
This convention caught on quickly around Carnegie Mellon, and soon spread to other universities and research labs via the primitive computer networks of the day.\'a0 (Some CMU alumni who had moved on to other places continued to read our bboards as a way of keeping in touch with their old community.)\
\'a0\
Within a few months, we started seeing the lists with dozens of \'93smilies\'94: open-mouthed surprise, person wearing glasses, Abraham Lincoln, Santa Claus, the pope, and so on.\'a0 Producing such clever compilations has become a serious hobby for some people.\'a0 But only my two original smilies, plus the \'93winky\'94\'a0 ;-)\'a0 and the \'93noseless\'94 variants seem to be in common use for actual communication.\'a0 It\'92s interesting to note that Microsoft and AOL now intercept these character strings and turn them into little pictures.\'a0 Personally, I think this destroys the whimsical element of the original.\
\'a0\
Unfortunately, I didn\'92t keep a copy of my original post.\'a0 It didn\'92t seem like a big deal at the time.\'a0 By the time I realized that this smiley-face phenomenon was going to be long-lasting and that it would spread around the world as the Internet grew, it was too late to easily retrieve the post, and the original message was lost for many years.\
\'a0\
Several attempts to find the post on old backup tapes were unsuccessful.\'a0 But in 2001-2002 Mike Jones of Microsoft sponsored a more serious \'93archeological dig\'94 through our ancient backup tapes.\'a0 Jeff Baird and\'a0 the CMU CS facilities staff put in a heroic effort with the support and encouragement of Howard Wactlar, Bob Cosgrove, and David Livingston.\'a0 They found the proper tapes, located a working tape drive that could read the ancient media, decoded the old formats, and did a lot of searching to find the actual posts.\'a0 I am most grateful to all who participated in this successful quest, which I call the \'93Digital Coelacanth Project.\'94\
\'a0\
