As you can see, the note in which I suggested this thing was quite short and casual \'96 just part of an ongoing discussion that involved many people.\'a0 I apparently didn\'92t even read it over before posting, since a word or two were dropped in editing.\'a0 I do remember writing a longer message in which I explained the need for a humor-marker in more detail, and suggested the :-) symbol, along with :-( to indicate anger or real unhappiness.\'a0 But this longer message must have come later \'96 perhaps a later bboardpost or an E-mail message that I sent to someone.\'a0 In any case, that more detailed post did not turn up in our search.\
\'a0\
Many people have denounced the very idea of the smiley face, pointing out that good writers should have no need to explicitly label their humorous comments.\'a0 Shakespeare and Jonathan Swift and Mark Twain got along just fine without this.\'a0 And by labeling the remarks that are not meant to be taken seriously, we spoil the joke.\'a0 In satirical writing, half the fun is in never being quite sure whether the author is serious or not.\
\'a0\
To a large degree, I agree with these critics.\'a0 Perhaps the E-mail smiley face has done more to degrade our written communication than to improve it.\'a0 But in defense of the idea, let me say two things:\
\'a0\
First, not all people who post on boards have the literary skill of\'a0 Shakespeare or Twain, and even those luminaries had bad days.\'a0 If Shakespeare were tossing off a quick note complaining about the lack of employee parking spaces near the Globe Theater, he might have produced the same kind of sloppy prose that the rest of us do.\'a0 Besides, Shakespeare\'92s work is full of clich\'e9s and his spelling was atrocious.\'a0 :-)\
\'a0\
Second, and more important, these authors were publishing their words in a different medium, with different properties.\'a0 If 100,000 copies of\'a0 a novel or an essay were distributed in printed form, and if 1% of the readers didn\'92t get the joke and were outraged at what they had read, there was nothing these clueless readers could do to spoil the enjoyment of the other 99%.\'a0 But if it were possible for each of the 1000 clueless readers to write a lengthy counter-argument and to flood these into the same distribution channels as the original work, and if others could then jump into the fray in similar fashion, you can see the problems that this would cause.\'a0 If the judicious use of a few smilies can reduce the frequency of such firestorms, then maybe it\'92s not such a bad idea after all.\'a0 Again, we\'92re talking here about casual writing on the Internet, not great works printed in a one-way medium that is relatively inaccessible to the general public.\
\'a0\
One final point:\'a0 I\'92ve seen various claims that the sideways smiley face, built from ASCII characters, was invented by someone else.\'a0 I believe that I invented this particular glyph and the \'93turn your head to one side\'94 principle 
