\outl0\strokewidth0 independently
\i0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 .\'a0 I don\'92t recall seeing anything like this before my 1982 post, though a few messages in the thread we just located come close.\'a0 Leonard Hamey\'92s post suggesting (#) for humor might be taken as an example of \'93turn your head to one side\'94 \'96 it\'92s not really clear if that was his intent \'96 and apparently \\__/ was used by one of our research groups to indicate a smile.\'a0\
\'a0\
Some people have told me that the :-) or :)\'a0 convention was used by teletype operators in the old days.\'a0 Maybe so.\'a0 Others have written to tell me that their father or uncle or they themselves used to type these symbols, or something close to them, in private letters (or, in one case, on punch cards) long before 1982.\'a0 I haven\'92t (yet) seen any hard evidence of this, but I have no reason to doubt their accounts.\'a0 It\'92s a simple and obvious idea after all, and the independent invention of this idea by multiple people would not be implausible.\
\'a0\
So, the smiley idea may have appeared and disappeared a few times before my 1982 post.\'a0 I probably was not the first person ever to type these three letters in sequence, perhaps even with the meaning of \'93I\'92m just kidding\'94 and perhaps even online.\'a0 But I do believe that my 1982 suggestion was the one that finally took hold, spread around the world, and spawned thousands of variations.\'a0 My colleagues and I have been able to watch the idea spread out through the world\'92s computer networks from that original post.\
